snippet.textDisplay: Seeing more and more of this and when you know about flying and flight safety it's simply unacceptable.  These airlines and pilots are placing hundreds of lives at risk per flight just to save money when what they should be doing is flying someplace else nearby that isn't experiencing such strong weather conditions and either landing there...or simply cancelling and then rescheduling the flight for safety reasons.  It's getting to the point where they are becoming so preoccupied about whether their pilots can...that they aren't stopping to think seriously about whether they should.  Sooner or later one of these birds is going to flip hard, bury the engines and wing, roll the damned plane and kill everyone on board.  It's time for these pilots to stop "hot dogging" like they are in fighter jets  and remember there are hundreds of living people sitting behind them who want to get home safely.

snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, this is absolutely not a textbook landing at all... This is a very bad landing in fact. Don’t get defensive people, let me explain: A textbook crosswind landing is one where you come towards the runway crabbing, but where you smoothly straighten the aircraft as you flare in order to land parallel to the runway axis. Some aircraft (like the B52) indeed have main wheels that allow them to land at an angle by turning towards the runway axis in order to minimise the stress put on the strut. But nowhere near that angle. Truth is, this aircraft probably required an inspection by engineers after that sort of landing, just think how much stress was put on the main wheels ! It looks like the aircraft was at least 35 degrees off the runway axis, perhaps 45...

Here is what Airbus manuals say (for aviation enthusiasts):

The recommended de-crab technique is to use all of the following:

The rudder to align the aircraft with the runway heading during the flare

The roll control, if needed, to maintain the aircraft on the runway centerline. Any tendency to drift downwind should be counteracted by an appropriate lateral (roll) input on the sidestick.

In the case of strong crosswind, in the de-crab phase, the PF should be prepared to add small bank angle into the wind in order to maintain the aircraft on the runway centerline. The aircraft may be landed with a partial de-crab (residual crab angle up to about 5 °) to prevent an excessive bank. This technique prevents wingtip/sharklet (or engine nacelle) strike caused by an excessive bank angle.

As a consequence, this may result in touching down with some bank angle into the wind (hence with the upwind landing gear first).

Here, The pilot comes crabbing, that’s fine and absolutely normal, but then, he floats over the runway for a long time at around 10-20 ft. The wind starts pushing him towards the grass, but still, he floats and does not correct the attitude of the aircraft to put it on the ground. Instead, he uses rudder to get back on the centreline, but increases the angle with the runway axis, putting the struts and tyres at risk on touchdown. The best course of action here would have actually been to go around. (Before I get ripped by simmers, I’m not trying to be a d***, I am an airline pilot, I did fly in Ciara and Dennis and man, these were interesting days for all of us for sure... I’m just explaining for those interested in aviation.)

snippet.textDisplay: That was atrocious! Should have gone around, where would you like me to start? Let’s start with the over flair causing the Aircraft to go up not down, so that’s the first GA right there, but no he try’s to continue and as the energy leaves the Aircraft the drift angle increases, please note at this point no attempt has been made to align the aircraft with the runway? So now the sink takes over and there is no time or energy left to align so even if full power was applied he/she will touch the ground, the touchdown happens with at least 18 degrees of drift and I’m being kind here because it looks like way more, this is potentially damaging to the undercarriage as it’s not designed to encounter large side loads, and now the threat to safety is that the Aircraft is pointed off the runway, so a massive rudder application is made to prevent a runway excursion, had it not been for the wet runway this flight could well have been a statistic.

snippet.textDisplay:
ETIHAD IS NOT IMPRESSED; quoted-

A leaked memo from Etihad’s own pilot training department would suggest the airline wasn’t quite so impressed with the pilot’s efforts during Storm Dennis.

“You may have seen a video this week of one of our A380s landing in a strong crosswind in London,” the memo from Etihad’s manager of flight crew training for its Boeing fleet starts off.

“Initially the landing was seen by some as a ‘masterful landing,'” the memo continues.

“If you see such a thing in the sim (aircraft simulator) that would be a grade 1 for both pilots… Please gentlemen, let’s teach our pilots to operate safely even that means changing the mission.”
